11. Hierarchical Inheritance
class Shape {
    void display() { System.out.println("Displaying shape info..."); }
}

class Circle extends Shape {
    void area(double r) { System.out.println("Circle Area: " + (3.14 * r * r)); }
}

class Rectangle extends Shape {
    void area(int l, int b) { System.out.println("Rectangle Area: " + (l * b)); }
}

12. Payment System (Abstraction)
​Abstract methods force subclasses to provide specific logic (e.g., how to pay).
abstract class Payment {
    abstract void pay(double amount);
}

class CreditCardPayment extends Payment {
    void pay(double amount) { System.out.println("Paid ₹" + amount + " via Credit Card."); }
}

class UPIPayment extends Payment {
    void pay(double amount) { System.out.println("Paid ₹" + amount + " via UPI."); }
}

13 & 14. Runtime Polymorphism & Multilevel Inheritance
​Runtime Polymorphism occurs when a parent class reference points to a child class object, and the overridden method is called at execution time.
// Task 14: Multilevel Inheritance
class Person {
    void role() { System.out.println("I am a Person."); }
}

class Employee extends Person {
    @Override
    void role() { System.out.println("I am an Employee."); }
}

class Manager extends Employee {
    @Override
    void role() { System.out.println("I am a Manager."); }
}

// In Main: 
// Person p = new Manager(); 
// p.role(); // Outputs "I am a Manager" (Dynamic Method Dispatch)

15. Ride Booking (Array of Objects)
abstract class Ride {
    double distance;
    Ride(double d) { this.distance = d; }
    abstract void calculateFare();
}

class BikeRide extends Ride {
    BikeRide(double d) { super(d); }
    void calculateFare() { System.out.println("Bike Fare: ₹" + (distance * 5)); }
}
// Repeat logic for AutoRide (*8) and CarRide (*12)

16. Hospital Staff (Method Overriding)
class Staff { void work() { System.out.println("Staff is working."); } }
class Doctor extends Staff { void work() { System.out.println("Doctor treats patients."); } }
class Nurse extends Staff { void work() { System.out.println("Nurse assists patients."); } }


17. Static Variable (Employee Counter)
​The static keyword makes a variable shared across all instances of a class.
class Employee {
    static int employeeCount = 0;
    String name;

    Employee(String name) {
        this.name = name;
        employeeCount++; // Increments for every new object
    }

    static void showCount() {
        System.out.println("Total Employees: " + employeeCount);
    }
}


18. Final Variable
​A final variable's value cannot be changed once initialized.
class Bank {
    final double interestRate = 7.5; // Constant

    void calculateInterest(double amount) {
        System.out.println("Interest: " + (amount * interestRate / 100));
    }
}


19. Array of Book Objects.
class Book {
    String title, author;
    double price;

    Book(String t, String a, double p) { title = t; author = a; price = p; }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Book[] library = new Book[2];
        library[0] = new Book("Java Basics", "Author A", 500);
        library[1] = new Book("OOP Concepts", "Author B", 600);

        for (Book b : library) {
            System.out.println(b.title + " by " + b.author + " costs " + b.price);
        }
    }
}


20. The 'this' Keyword
​The this keyword resolves ambiguity when parameter names match instance variable names.
class Employee {
    String name;
    double salary;

    Employee(String name, double salary) {
        this.name = name;      // 'this.name' refers to the class variable
        this.salary = salary;  // 'salary' refers to the parameter
    }

    void display() {
        System.out.println("Name: " + name + ", Salary: " + salary);
    }
}

